410→                           Erdős and Gallai <a href="#cite-ErGa59-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGa59','1020'); return false;">[ErGa59]</a> proved this is true when $r=2$ (when $r=2$ this also follows from the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s%E2%80%93Ko%E2%80%93Rado_theorem" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">Erdős-Ko-Rado theorem</a>).<br><br>The conjectured form of $f(n;r,k)$ is the best possible, as witnessed by two examples: all $r$-edges on a set of $rk-1$ many vertices, and all edges on a set of $n$ vertices which contain at least one element of a fixed set of $k-1$ vertices. <br><br>Frankl <a href="#cite-Fr87-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Fr87','1020'); return false;">[Fr87]</a> proved $f(n;r,k) \leq (k-1)\binom{n-1}{r-1}$.<br><br>This is sometimes known as the Erdős matching conjecture. Note that the second term in the maximum dominates when $n\geq (r+1)k$. There are many partial results towards this, establishing the conjecture in different ranges. These can be separated into two regimes. For small $n$:<ul>
411→<li>The conjecture is trivially true if $n&lt;kr$.</li>
412→<li>Kleitman <a href="#cite-Kl68-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Kl68','1020'); return false;">[Kl68]</a> when $n=kr$.</li>
413→<li>Frankl <a href="#cite-Fr17-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Fr17','1020'); return false;">[Fr17]</a> when\[kr \leq n\leq k\left(r+\frac{1}{2r^{2r+1}}\right).\]</li>
414→<li>Kolupaev and Kupavskii <a href="#cite-KoKu23-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('KoKu23','1020'); return false;">[KoKu23]</a> when $r\geq 5$, $k&gt;101r^3$, and\[kr \leq n &lt; k\left(r+\frac{1}{100r}\right).\]</li>
415→</ul>For large $n$:<ul>
416→<li>Erdős <a href="#cite-Er65d-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er65d','1020'); return false;">[Er65d]</a> when $n&gt;kc_r$ (where $c_r$ depends on $r$ in some unspecified fashion).</li>
417→<li> Frankl and Füredi <a href="#cite-Fr87-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Fr87','1020'); return false;">[Fr87]</a> when $n&gt;100 k^2r$.</li>
418→<li> Bollobás, Daykin, and Erdős <a href="#cite-BDE76-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('BDE76','1020'); return false;">[BDE76]</a> when $n\geq 2kr^3$.</li>
419→<li> Frankl, Rödl, and Ruciński <a href="#cite-FRR12-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('FRR12','1020'); return false;">[FRR12]</a> when $r=3$ and $n\geq 4k$.</li>
420→<li> Huang, Loh, and Sudakov <a href="#cite-HLS12-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('HLS12','1020'); return false;">[HLS12]</a> when $n\geq 3kr^2$.</li>
421→<li> Frankl, Luczak, and Mieczkowska <a href="#cite-FLM12-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('FLM12','1020'); return false;">[FLM12]</a> when $n&gt; 2k\frac{r^2}{\log r}$.</li>
422→<li> Luczak and Mieczkowska <a href="#cite-LuMi14-1020" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('LuMi14','1020'); return false;">[LuMi14]</a> when $r=3$ (for all $k$).</li>
423→</ul>
